## Abstract

The existing `/invoke` endpoint (V0/V1) returns a Leo-specific envelope (`GepReturnDto`) that drops widgets, has no ordering between text and widgets, leaks internal state, and does not validate inputs. It works as a chat-UI fallback, but not when an agent is called as an API ŌĆö by another service, an automation, or a third-party integration.

Invoke V2 replaces it with `POST /v2/workflow-engine/:id/invoke`, which returns an **A2A Message** (Google's open Agent-to-Agent protocol): an ordered `parts[]` of text and widgets, plus a clean `metadata` block.

> **TL;DR** ŌĆö V2 runs the same streaming pipeline as `/stream` and a subscriber (`A2AStreamCollector`) assembles the AG-UI event stream into an A2A Message. No new state variables, no schema changes required on existing workflows.

---

## 1. Why this ADR exists

### 1.1 The two ways agents are consumed today

| Transport       | Endpoint                              | Who calls it                            |
| --------------- | ------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| Streaming (SSE) | `POST /workflow-engine/:id/stream`    | Chat UI, copilots, embedded assistants  |
| Invoke (V0/V1)  | `POST /workflow-engine/:id/invoke`    | Legacy server-to-server callers         |

The streaming path is feature-complete: it carries text tokens, tool calls, step events, widgets, HITL interrupts, and reasoning events ŌĆö all as AG-UI events.

The invoke path was bolted on later. It blocks on `compiledGraph.invoke()` and returns:

```json
{
  "isSuccess": true,
  "returnValue": {
    "messages": [ "..." ],
    "selectedAgentId": "...",
    "state": { "flow": {}, "system": {}, "nodes": {} }
  }
}
```

### 1.2 What's wrong with it

- **Widgets are lost.** PV widgets are dispatched as `CUSTOM` SSE events (`PV_PRE_RENDER` / `PV_TEMPLATE` / `PV_POST_RENDER`). The blocking `invoke()` path never sees them.
- **No content ordering.** If an agent produces `text ŌåÆ widget ŌåÆ text`, there is no way to represent that sequence in the response.
- **Proprietary format.** Every consumer has to learn `GepReturnDto`. No open standard.
- **State leaks.** `flow` / `system` / `nodes` are exposed alongside the answer, with no separation between "the answer" and "internals".
- **No input validation.** A badly shaped request starts executing anyway; the LLM sees garbage and either hallucinates or crashes mid-run.

### 1.3 Why now

Product direction is moving toward **agents as APIs** ŌĆö callable by other services, automations, agent-to-agent orchestrators, and external integrations. Those consumers need a structured, ordered, standards-compliant response. V1 does not deliver that.

### 1.4 Goals

| ID   | Goal                                                                                  | Priority |
| ---- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------- |
| G1   | Return A2A `Message { message_id, role, parts[], metadata }` (open standard)          | P0       |
| G2   | Preserve the order of text and widgets as the agent produced them                      | P0       |
| G3   | Include widgets (PV, A2UI) as first-class parts with `media_type`                      | P0       |
| G4   | Clean separation ŌĆö `parts[]` is the answer, `metadata` is side-channel info            | P0       |
| G5   | No duplicated logic between stream and invoke                                          | P0       |
| G6   | HITL interrupts surface on invoke, not just stream                                     | P0       |
| G7   | Validate inputs before execution starts                                                | P1       |
| G8   | Graceful fallback for workflows that do not emit events                                | P1       |
| G9   | `/stream` stays untouched                                                              | P0       |
| G10  | Works on existing workflows with zero schema changes                                   | P1       |

